00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:50.320
haven't the foggiest idea
of what the technology

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:53.100
landscape here is now.

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:54.560
I brought a friend
with me today.

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:56.770
His name is Mr.
Willie Lyles Bay.

00:11:56.770 --> 00:11:58.880
He served 45 years.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:00.040
45 years.

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:03.880
And he's an example of
the type of individuals

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:05.830
that we're working with
in order to give them

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:09.370
the skill sets to be able to
meet some of the employment

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:12.030
barriers that we're
having in our community.

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:15.550
ERIK BURGESS: Thank you.

00:12:15.550 --> 00:12:17.960
I think education is very
pivotal, like he said,

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:24.780
for individuals who are
going through a transition

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:25.875
of coming home.

00:12:25.875 --> 00:12:28.020
It'll afford you
more opportunities,

00:12:28.020 --> 00:12:30.180
more marketable skills.

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:33.060
Like, when I was in prison, the
only thing we had was college.

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:35.920
There wasn't no type of skill or
trades where we can learn from.

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:38.190
So I say some of
that education was

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.802
based on antiquated
theories and something

00:12:40.802 --> 00:12:42.510
that we couldn't apply
when we come home.

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:46.350
So basically, what component we
had to have was the attitude.

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:49.710
So we had the attitude
to change and pursue

00:12:49.710 --> 00:12:54.030
other avenues of being
successful out here.

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:56.400
Like I said, I'm in
school now at Wayne State,

00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:00.110
taking up psychology, and I'll
be graduating in the spring.

00:13:00.110 --> 00:13:03.570
So that's one way I'm trying
to make myself more marketable.

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:05.790
I'm in the process of becoming
a social entrepreneur,

00:13:05.790 --> 00:13:09.060
where I can have an
impact on quality of life.

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:10.140
JACOB SMITH: Great.

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:14.220
And so, Aaron, you touched
on this just briefly,

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:16.530
and I've talked about it
with a number of people

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:17.940
on this panel in the past.

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:21.060
But educational
opportunities in terms

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:24.990
of while you're in prison,
what types of options exist?

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:28.380
You mentioned bringing back
Pell Grants, for example.

00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:30.990
Erik, I know we've talked
a lot about your GIS

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:34.410
training and the self-education
that you were doing

00:13:34.410 --> 00:13:36.780
with technology magazines.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.780
Could you guys speak to
while you are incarcerated

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:42.030
what types of opportunities
are available if somebody

00:13:42.030 --> 00:13:45.330
is proactive if they
want to be taking

00:13:45.330 --> 00:13:47.610
that power into their
own hands as it currently

00:13:47.610 --> 00:13:50.961
stands in Michigan but
more broadly speaking?

00:13:50.961 --> 00:13:55.470
ERIK BURGESS: Michigan, firstly,
the most basic education

00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:59.250
to have, unfortunately, is
a GED, a General Education

00:13:59.250 --> 00:14:03.390
Diploma, which, at least, I
think 40% of prison population

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:05.140
do not have a GED,
unfortunately--

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:07.560
a lack of education as
Carlos had reiterated.

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:09.750
That's one reason
why the incarceration

00:14:09.750 --> 00:14:13.070
rates are going up.

00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:14.220
I changed my attitude.

00:14:14.220 --> 00:14:16.130
Like Carlos said, I
wasn't illiterate.

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:17.606
I wasn't dumb.

00:14:17.606 --> 00:14:19.980
I changed my attitude because
I wanted to prepare myself,

00:14:19.980 --> 00:14:22.080
and I had a plan for
when I come home.

00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:26.460
So I became a GED tutor--

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:28.470
and once the opportunity
came up to learn GIS

00:14:28.470 --> 00:14:30.660
because I know that's
the way the landscape

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:32.575
and the format of the
world was going to.

00:14:32.575 --> 00:14:34.200
I wanted to have some
type of knowledge

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:37.680
where I can be more marketable,
have some type of skills

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:38.790
to advance myself.

00:14:38.790 --> 00:14:41.427
And [INAUDIBLE] doesn't
make my family proud.

00:14:41.427 --> 00:14:43.510
That's what I wanted to
do-- make my family proud.

00:14:43.510 --> 00:14:46.290
Because they're also going
through an incarceration period

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:47.310
too, also.

00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:49.680
And some individuals
do not understand

00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:53.050
how it's a very burden
on your family as well.

00:14:53.050 --> 00:14:55.800
So if you have family
in your corner,

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:58.840
I think we're obligated,
not only to ourselves,

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:01.230
to our family, we're also
obligated to our community.

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:04.170
And I think we're the epitome
and the apex of what attitude

00:15:04.170 --> 00:15:07.590
can do as far as
changing your life

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:09.150
and changing your thoughts.

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:10.020
That's all it is.

00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:11.999
JACOB SMITH: When does
the teacher appear?

00:15:11.999 --> 00:15:13.790
ERIK BURGESS: When does
the teacher appear?

00:15:13.790 --> 00:15:15.706
The teacher appears when
the student is ready.

00:15:15.706 --> 00:15:16.540
And I stay ready.

00:15:19.330 --> 00:15:22.807
AARON KINZEL: So I think the
predominant form of education

00:15:22.807 --> 00:15:24.390
in all carceral
spaces, whether that's

00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:27.450
Michigan, or anywhere in the
US, or the federal systems

00:15:27.450 --> 00:15:29.350
is informal education.

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:31.170
And that was extremely
powerful for me

00:15:31.170 --> 00:15:33.630
because when I went
into the system,

00:15:33.630 --> 00:15:36.330
I was a high school
dropout, 18-year-old kid.

00:15:36.330 --> 00:15:38.207
I ended up taking my
GED in the county jail

00:15:38.207 --> 00:15:39.290
when I was awaiting trial.

00:15:39.290 --> 00:15:41.340
So that was like my
first little piece.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:43.380
So a lot of institutions
do have GED,

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:45.900
which I think is a great
step in the right direction

00:15:45.900 --> 00:15:50.250
to help with those basic skills
with literacy, math, et cetera,

00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:52.510
but there's very few
college programs anymore.

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:54.720
So in 1994, the
Omnibus Crime Bill

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:56.520
passed under the
Clinton administration,

00:15:56.520 --> 00:15:58.770
which destroyed Pell Grant
eligibility for prisoners

00:15:58.770 --> 00:15:59.760
nationwide.

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:01.720
And in my personal and
professional opinion,

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:03.240
this was the most
devastating piece

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:08.250
of public policy that has ever
crossed a congressional space.

00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:11.250
It destroyed college
education nationwide.

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:13.920
And fast forward
now, we're in 2018.

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:15.930
There's very few educational
opportunities that

00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:17.710
are post-secondary in nature.

00:16:17.710 --> 00:16:20.700
However, in Michigan, we
do have a Pell Grant pilot,

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:22.920
which was sponsored by the
US Department of Education

00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:24.600
under the Obama administration.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:27.060
And Michigan does have several
sites in which prisoners

00:16:27.060 --> 00:16:29.460
are gaining Pell Grants
and actually earning

00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:31.590
associate's and bachelor's
degrees right now, which

00:16:31.590 --> 00:16:33.630
I think is extremely powerful.

00:16:33.630 --> 00:16:36.060
And again, there's
research to back it up,

00:16:36.060 --> 00:16:39.270
where recidivism rates go down,
but also just anecdotally,

00:16:39.270 --> 00:16:41.400
anyone that I know that's
had some type education

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:44.790
in the system is employed.

00:16:44.790 --> 00:16:47.920
They have a better grasp on
their family connections.

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:49.720
They're civically
engaged citizens.

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:52.650
There's so many things
that they're improving upon

00:16:52.650 --> 00:16:55.800
because they become educated
and become civically engaged.

00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:58.080
And that makes them more
likely to stay out in society

00:16:58.080 --> 00:17:00.264
and be productive and
taxpayers citizens.

00:17:00.264 --> 00:17:01.680
There's such a tax
base that we're

00:17:01.680 --> 00:17:03.900
losing by really
disenfranchising

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:06.030
people that have been
locked up in the system.

00:17:06.030 --> 00:17:09.150
And we're losing economic
growth as a nation.

00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:11.190
And there's so much of
this technology stuff.

00:17:11.190 --> 00:17:14.430
And with Google here, I
think that's the future.

00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:17.099
If we can think about ways
to integrate more technology

00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:19.599
in the prison space and for
people coming home, too,

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:21.739
who may lack the skills--

00:17:21.739 --> 00:17:23.369
like, when I came
home, the new hotness

00:17:23.369 --> 00:17:26.604
was those Motorola razor
flip phones in 2007.

00:17:26.604 --> 00:17:28.770
I don't know if any of you
remember those, but like,

00:17:28.770 --> 00:17:30.270
this texting was
like, holy shit.

00:17:30.270 --> 00:17:31.080
Like, oh my god.

00:17:31.080 --> 00:17:32.430
Like, we can text.

00:17:32.430 --> 00:17:36.030
And now, we all got
our smartphones that

00:17:36.030 --> 00:17:37.800
can do just about anything.

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:40.480
And for someone that's been
down 10, 20, or 30 years,

00:17:40.480 --> 00:17:43.120
that's just like being like
dropped into Shangri-La

00:17:43.120 --> 00:17:45.000
and you have no idea what to do.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.960
So I really congratulate you,
Carlos, for helping people out

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:50.400
on that because that's
a much-needed piece

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:53.567
of re-education in
those populations.

00:17:53.567 --> 00:17:55.275
KARLOS L. HARRIS: So
part of my process--

00:17:58.380 --> 00:17:59.910
so I have some college.

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:01.020
I'm a college dropout.

00:18:01.020 --> 00:18:03.654
I was going to school for
business computer science.

00:18:03.654 --> 00:18:05.820
And I can remember one of
the last professors I had.

00:18:05.820 --> 00:18:08.070
He told me I didn't know the
difference between there,

00:18:08.070 --> 00:18:11.480
their, and they're;
to, too, and two.

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:14.630
So one of the first
things that I accomplished

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:17.720
while incarcerated was
I began to read as much

00:18:17.720 --> 00:18:20.180
as I could get my hands on.

00:18:20.180 --> 00:18:23.630
Because I wanted to know.

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:25.970
And it was through
that reading--

00:18:25.970 --> 00:18:29.030
you know, everybody in prison
says I'm writing my book,

00:18:29.030 --> 00:18:29.810
right?

00:18:29.810 --> 00:18:32.420
So I was able to write for
novels that when I came home

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:34.220
I self-published.

00:18:34.220 --> 00:18:36.940
And it was through
that trajectory

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:39.380
that I landed myself
at a point to saying

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:41.870
that I can do something
other than the crime that

00:18:41.870 --> 00:18:44.210
was taking me to prison.

00:18:44.210 --> 00:18:47.630
You know, so many
of the guys that I

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:49.835
come into contact with now--

00:18:49.835 --> 00:18:50.750
I say it like this.

00:18:50.750 --> 00:18:52.130
I'm really blessed.

00:18:52.130 --> 00:18:54.230
Because after having
served the time,

00:18:54.230 --> 00:18:56.570
I'm able now to go
back into the prisons

00:18:56.570 --> 00:18:59.840
to meet these
gentlemen and women.

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:05.240
And prison wasn't like
that when I came through.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:07.850
We didn't have the
opportunities, right?

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:13.010
So Aaron speaks about
the Pell Grant initiative

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:15.600
that MDOC had a few years ago.

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:17.870
Well, because of the
Second Chance grant,

00:19:17.870 --> 00:19:21.440
we actually have a contract
with MDOC in which we go in

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.420
and we train--

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:28.520
I think it's 119 individuals
that's allocated to a program

00:19:28.520 --> 00:19:30.390
that we have in technology--

00:19:30.390 --> 00:19:32.010
information technology.

00:19:32.010 --> 00:19:35.390
And so the research is that
we would train them inside.

00:19:35.390 --> 00:19:38.540
And once they return back
here to Wayne County,

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:41.030
we actually are getting
them a place in employment

00:19:41.030 --> 00:19:44.630
opportunities that otherwise
they wouldn't have access to,

00:19:44.630 --> 00:19:45.130
you know?

00:19:45.130 --> 00:19:48.230
And that's through
the Labor Department.

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:53.670
That wasn't there when I
came through the department.

00:19:53.670 --> 00:19:57.410
And I think that the more we
have conversations like this

00:19:57.410 --> 00:20:02.030
and we have those innovators
like a Mr. Burgess

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:05.850
that are futured or forward
thinking in their approach,

00:20:05.850 --> 00:20:08.720
the more we can begin to
help more of our community

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:11.540
that are returning home.

00:20:11.540 --> 00:20:15.350
You have guys that spent 40
years that literally do not

00:20:15.350 --> 00:20:19.040
have the skill sets to
send a simple email.

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:20.900
That's something we
take for granted.

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:24.200
And I promise you, it's
painful to see a person

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:28.330
stand at a computer and tell
you they can't turn it on.

00:20:28.330 --> 00:20:32.790
So that's one of the
biggest things I and my team

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:37.110
are trying to dismantle
across the department.

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:39.750
We're mainly in Michigan
now because that's

00:20:39.750 --> 00:20:41.480
kind of like a foothold for us.

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:44.220
And it's to make sure that
those that are returning back

00:20:44.220 --> 00:20:47.310
to our communities at
least have some technology

00:20:47.310 --> 00:20:50.370
savvy about themselves to
where they can simply fill out

00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:53.430
these online applications and
have access to the employment

00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:55.500
opportunities that we all
just take for granted.

00:21:00.012 --> 00:21:00.970
IMANI MIXON: Thank you.

00:21:00.970 --> 00:21:03.730
And it sounds like you all
sort of found your own ways

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:05.470
to educate yourself
and go on a journey

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:07.180
after transitioning out.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:09.640
But we know hindsight is 20/20.

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:12.220
So what do you wish
you knew upon re-entry?

00:21:17.730 --> 00:21:20.970
Anybody?

00:21:20.970 --> 00:21:24.660
KARLOS L. HARRIS: I
wish someone had really

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:29.345
told me about your network
determines your net worth.

00:21:29.345 --> 00:21:31.220
You know, my grandmother
used to always say--

00:21:31.220 --> 00:21:31.969
I'm from Arkansas.

00:21:31.969 --> 00:21:33.090
I'm sorry.

00:21:33.090 --> 00:21:35.730
So my grandmother used to always
say, birds of a feather flock

00:21:35.730 --> 00:21:37.180
together.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:38.250
And that's so true.

00:21:38.250 --> 00:21:39.270
Now that I'm older--

00:21:39.270 --> 00:21:40.950
I'll be 46 next month.

00:21:40.950 --> 00:21:45.330
And I've learned in my older
age now that the people that I

00:21:45.330 --> 00:21:49.170
really associate
with, they kind of

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:52.740
have an influence
on my future, right?

00:21:52.740 --> 00:21:57.305
One of the first clients
that I got when I became--

00:21:57.305 --> 00:22:00.540
I opened my digital marketing
agency was a judge that

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:02.610
sits over at 36 district now.

00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:04.710
He called me to his
office because he

00:22:04.710 --> 00:22:08.700
heard about this returning
citizen that does websites.

00:22:08.700 --> 00:22:12.240
And so he called me over,
and here I am in his chamber.

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:15.570
And I'm thinking,
wow, I'm literally

00:22:15.570 --> 00:22:18.470
in the back room with a judge.

00:22:18.470 --> 00:22:21.240
If not for technology,
if not for me

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:24.330
seeing an opportunity
for me in this space,

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:28.320
I would've never had that
opportunity, you know?

00:22:28.320 --> 00:22:32.100
Because the crimes
that I committed--

00:22:32.100 --> 00:22:33.690
I did burglary.

00:22:33.690 --> 00:22:39.300
And whenever I sat
and, I did the résumés,

00:22:39.300 --> 00:22:41.700
I would always be told
that I couldn't get the job

00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:44.850
because they were
crimes of dishonesty.

00:22:44.850 --> 00:22:48.960
So technically, I wasn't
about to get a job pretty much

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:49.930
anywhere.

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:52.990
So I had to be creative
in my approach.

00:22:52.990 --> 00:22:56.050
And I just wish someone
had sat and told me many,

00:22:56.050 --> 00:22:59.670
many years ago to really
start to position myself

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:05.010
with a network of individuals
that could actually

00:23:05.010 --> 00:23:08.220
shift my mindset into
a better direction

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:10.350
to where I wanted to go.

00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:14.350
Because I like to think I
never was really a bad person.

00:23:14.350 --> 00:23:16.030
I think we all probably
would say that.

00:23:16.030 --> 00:23:19.950
But at the same time, had I been
with more like-minded people,

00:23:19.950 --> 00:23:22.650
the travel wouldn't have been
as long as it has been for me.

00:23:25.716 --> 00:23:30.060
ERIK BURGESS: The one thing I
wish I knew is how to listen--

00:23:32.690 --> 00:23:33.550
is how to listen.

00:23:33.550 --> 00:23:35.360
We learn that when
we're younger--

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:36.300
just how to listen.

00:23:36.300 --> 00:23:38.250
You have to know how
to listen to learn,

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:39.960
and so that's one thing I wish--

00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:41.280
I didn't listen.

00:23:41.280 --> 00:23:44.730
And signs and symbols around
me, especially my grandpa,

00:23:44.730 --> 00:23:45.840
why did you do that, boy?

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:47.002
You don't have to do that.

00:23:47.002 --> 00:23:48.960
That's the only thing
that resonated in my mind

00:23:48.960 --> 00:23:49.959
when I was incarcerated.

00:23:49.959 --> 00:23:50.896
Why did you do that?

00:23:50.896 --> 00:23:52.020
You didn't have to do that.

00:23:52.020 --> 00:23:52.800
You wasn't illiterate.

00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:53.550
You wasn't stupid.

00:23:53.550 --> 00:23:54.920
You had everything you had.

00:23:54.920 --> 00:23:57.930
But I made the
choice to be foolish

00:23:57.930 --> 00:24:02.820
and made a very
[INAUDIBLE] decision that

00:24:02.820 --> 00:24:05.079
cost me almost my entire life.

00:24:05.079 --> 00:24:07.620
So when I got incarcerated, I
was sentenced to mandatory life

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:09.900
without no parole,
which means they

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:11.790
wanted me to die in prison.

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:14.700
And I said, I'll
never die in prison.

00:24:14.700 --> 00:24:16.530
I'm not going to die in prison.

00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:18.940
Just like I walked
in, I'mma walk out.

00:24:18.940 --> 00:24:22.770
So thank God I'm here
to share my story,

00:24:22.770 --> 00:24:24.780
and I'll never go back--

00:24:24.780 --> 00:24:25.440
period.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:26.850
I'm never going back.

00:24:26.850 --> 00:24:29.190
And I want to congratulate
all of these individuals

00:24:29.190 --> 00:24:32.910
up here who have to
come to the forefront

00:24:32.910 --> 00:24:35.940
and be a prime example of what
attitude and what education

00:24:35.940 --> 00:24:36.940
can do for your life.

00:24:42.887 --> 00:24:44.720
AARON KINZEL: So I'll
just say really brief,

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:46.730
I'll piggyback off
what Carlos said.

00:24:46.730 --> 00:24:48.500
Networking is key.

00:24:48.500 --> 00:24:50.450
Again, I put out
hundreds of applications.

00:24:50.450 --> 00:24:51.640
I never got a call back.

00:24:51.640 --> 00:24:55.400
But when I started making deep
connections and relationships--

00:24:55.400 --> 00:24:57.410
like, my boss now,
ironically, is

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:59.102
a judge from Washtenaw County.

00:24:59.102 --> 00:25:01.310
He's the director of
criminology and criminal justice

00:25:01.310 --> 00:25:02.240
where I work now.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:05.030
So isn't that the kind
of ironic relationship--

00:25:05.030 --> 00:25:07.780
the felon and the judge.

00:25:07.780 --> 00:25:10.490
But I have great and deep
respect for this man,

00:25:10.490 --> 00:25:12.650
and he's been a
mentor to me, and I've

00:25:12.650 --> 00:25:14.000
learned a lot from him.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.380
And he sees in me opportunity
and spark of light.

00:25:17.380 --> 00:25:19.130
If there's one thing
I would want to know,

00:25:19.130 --> 00:25:21.920
besides the networking,
I would say,

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:24.680
reentry services should start
day one when you get locked up,

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:26.420
not when you come home.

00:25:26.420 --> 00:25:28.190
You should be getting
prepared day one.

00:25:28.190 --> 00:25:31.010
If you've got a 10-year bid on
your first day in the system,

00:25:31.010 --> 00:25:32.990
you should start
to build what you

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:35.630
need to do for reentry
services upon your release,

00:25:35.630 --> 00:25:38.750
and I know a lot of people
rarely ever do that.

00:25:38.750 --> 00:25:42.530
Secondary to that,
understanding trauma.

00:25:42.530 --> 00:25:44.540
Many people who go
into the carceral state

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:47.420
are already traumatized, and
that trauma is never addressed.

00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:50.150
A lot of people who are
convicted of felonies

00:25:50.150 --> 00:25:52.100
are survivors of crime.

00:25:52.100 --> 00:25:53.180
Myself, I was one.

00:25:53.180 --> 00:25:55.970
My stepfather tried to murder
me at the age of eight--

00:25:55.970 --> 00:25:57.837
and lots of other
abuse and violence

00:25:57.837 --> 00:25:59.420
that I was subjected
to, which I'm not

00:25:59.420 --> 00:26:02.170
saying that to not be
accountable for my crime,

00:26:02.170 --> 00:26:03.920
but it was certainly
a stepping stone that

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:05.880
led me into that direction.

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:08.690
And if we don't address
trauma in the carceral spaces,

00:26:08.690 --> 00:26:11.310
like solitary confinement,
being separated from families,

00:26:11.310 --> 00:26:13.531
all these different things,
when people come home,

00:26:13.531 --> 00:26:15.030
they don't know how
to deal with it.

00:26:15.030 --> 00:26:17.180
And I was certainly not
an exception to that rule.

00:26:17.180 --> 00:26:19.490
When I first came home, 10
years out of the system,

00:26:19.490 --> 00:26:21.404
that Motorola flip
phone was weird.

00:26:21.404 --> 00:26:22.070
That's a trauma.

00:26:22.070 --> 00:26:23.690
Technology, I get anxious.

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:24.695
I'm nervous.

00:26:24.695 --> 00:26:26.570
I feel like I'm stupid
because I don't really

00:26:26.570 --> 00:26:28.850
know how to work
technology and others do,

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:31.640
and I just don't know how to
really socially acclimate back

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:32.510
into society.

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:33.920
No one teaches us those skills.

00:26:33.920 --> 00:26:37.642
So understanding trauma and
having trauma-informed care

00:26:37.642 --> 00:26:39.100
right when you come
into the system

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:41.060
so you can start to address that
trauma so that when you come

00:26:41.060 --> 00:26:43.970
home, you're much more safer
and less likely to recidivate

00:26:43.970 --> 00:26:45.614
upon release.

00:26:45.614 --> 00:26:47.030
JACOB SMITH:
Michelle, do you have

00:26:47.030 --> 00:26:48.863
any incite you want to
share about the women

00:26:48.863 --> 00:26:50.756
in the program that might--

00:26:50.756 --> 00:26:53.210
MICHELLE SMART: So the
women that we service,

00:26:53.210 --> 00:26:55.310
our organization is fairly new.

00:26:55.310 --> 00:26:58.310
We just launched our
employment initiative

00:26:58.310 --> 00:27:02.270
in June of this year, where
we have hired four women.

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:05.570
On average, they serve
over 40 years in prison.

00:27:05.570 --> 00:27:09.780
And some of the things that
they have expressed-- actually,

00:27:09.780 --> 00:27:11.690
Michelle, I don't
think she minds

00:27:11.690 --> 00:27:14.240
me sharing-- that
Michelle Pearson joined

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:18.320
our organization in
September after serving

00:27:18.320 --> 00:27:19.800
34 years in prison.

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:23.180
This is her very first
job since coming home.

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:26.240
The ladies have
shared that being

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:29.360
reintegrated in the community
is very important to them.

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:30.720
They want to give back.

00:27:30.720 --> 00:27:32.910
They want to be looked
at who they are today.

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:35.400
They're trying to,
again, forget their past.

00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:37.740
They want to be accepted.

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:39.030
They want to work.

00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:42.920
They want to be recognized as
individuals who have already

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:43.820
paid their dues.

00:27:43.820 --> 00:27:45.620
Personally, I've
never been to prison.

00:27:45.620 --> 00:27:49.220
I have a family member, a
close friend, whose daughter

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:50.710
is currently incarcerated.

00:27:50.710 --> 00:27:54.440
So that's my passion for
helping women upon coming home.

00:27:54.440 --> 00:27:57.170
But they have shared
that getting out

00:27:57.170 --> 00:28:00.500
and engaged in the community and
getting the support that they

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:05.420
need as far as cell phones,
technology, education--

00:28:05.420 --> 00:28:08.160
even simple things as
going to the grocery store.

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:12.440
You've been away 34 years, 40
years, that's overwhelming.

00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:15.300
So our organization--
as I said, we

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:17.900
are doing things a
little different.

00:28:17.900 --> 00:28:20.870
Our ladies have a health
and wellness coach

00:28:20.870 --> 00:28:22.520
who comes in every Wednesday.

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:25.580
They do everything
from yoga to--

00:28:25.580 --> 00:28:26.810
they have fitness classes.

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:28.910
We have a conference room
that we call the gym.

00:28:28.910 --> 00:28:31.820
So we move things around
to accommodate the ladies.

00:28:31.820 --> 00:28:35.510
They have a life coach that
they meet with twice per month,

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:36.740
someone that they can go to.

00:28:36.740 --> 00:28:38.420
They don't all
have family members

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:41.060
that they can go to
if they're struggling

00:28:41.060 --> 00:28:44.570
or anyone that they can
share their struggles with.

00:28:44.570 --> 00:28:47.690
We also work with
a local bank who

00:28:47.690 --> 00:28:50.649
has helped them with things like
opening up a savings account.

00:28:50.649 --> 00:28:52.190
We want them to know
about budgeting.

00:28:52.190 --> 00:28:54.549
So they're coming back
to a whole new world,

00:28:54.549 --> 00:28:56.090
and they definitely
need the support.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:00.820
JACOB SMITH: And just to
