00:29:46.665 --> 00:29:47.230
What's that?

00:29:47.230 --> 00:29:47.850
IMANI MIXON:
Thereturningcitizen.org.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:49.830
JACOB SMITH: Yeah,
thereturningcitizen.org,

00:29:49.830 --> 00:29:51.480
absolutely.

00:29:51.480 --> 00:29:54.810
Great, well, moving
right along, so I'd

00:29:54.810 --> 00:29:58.360
love to hear from
you guys specific.

00:29:58.360 --> 00:30:01.590
We're here at the Google
Detroit headquarters.

00:30:01.590 --> 00:30:06.050
What specific opportunities
do you see through technology

00:30:06.050 --> 00:30:06.710
specifically?

00:30:06.710 --> 00:30:09.190
I know a few of you have
touched on this a little bit.

00:30:09.190 --> 00:30:12.750
I do want to point out that
this podcast wouldn't exist

00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:16.550
if Erik hadn't been reading
technology magazines in prison

00:30:16.550 --> 00:30:18.990
and heard about
podcasting, and this idea

00:30:18.990 --> 00:30:22.311
that a radio show could touch
people all over the world.

00:30:22.311 --> 00:30:24.060
That was how this
entire thing came about.

00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:26.550
Eric was like, I heard
about this really cool thing

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:27.810
called a podcast.

00:30:27.810 --> 00:30:29.610
Like, literally, that's
how that started.

00:30:29.610 --> 00:30:31.110
So I'm curious to
know, like, what--

00:30:31.110 --> 00:30:34.410
this is an example of how
technology can empower folks.

00:30:34.410 --> 00:30:36.870
What opportunities do you
see through technology?

00:30:36.870 --> 00:30:39.030
And then on the flip side,
what types of challenges

00:30:39.030 --> 00:30:41.436
do you see through technology?

00:30:47.268 --> 00:30:50.510
AARON KINZEL: So I think
there's a lot of opportunity

00:30:50.510 --> 00:30:51.219
for technology.

00:30:51.219 --> 00:30:53.510
Something that has been done
as a pilot in the Michigan

00:30:53.510 --> 00:30:55.975
Department of Corrections and
other correctional systems

00:30:55.975 --> 00:30:58.100
nationwide is they're
starting to integrate tablets

00:30:58.100 --> 00:31:00.080
into those carceral
spaces, which I think

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:01.592
is extremely powerful.

00:31:01.592 --> 00:31:03.050
And some people
will some kick-back

00:31:03.050 --> 00:31:05.466
on that saying that they're
kind of pimping the prisoners,

00:31:05.466 --> 00:31:07.674
but I really have
a pushback on that

00:31:07.674 --> 00:31:10.340
because they're making money off
these tablets-- which you know,

00:31:10.340 --> 00:31:11.540
Google's a corporation, too.

00:31:11.540 --> 00:31:13.010
No, I'm not hating on Google.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:14.642
You guys gotta make money.

00:31:14.642 --> 00:31:15.350
It is what it is.

00:31:15.350 --> 00:31:16.190
There's a bottom dollar.

00:31:16.190 --> 00:31:17.023
You gotta do things.

00:31:17.023 --> 00:31:19.430
But what I think is
extremely important

00:31:19.430 --> 00:31:21.890
is getting that technology
in those prison spaces

00:31:21.890 --> 00:31:23.990
where people are
able to start getting

00:31:23.990 --> 00:31:27.470
those technological skill sets.

00:31:27.470 --> 00:31:29.150
And something I'm
working on now is

00:31:29.150 --> 00:31:31.691
I'm trying to develop a pilot
with the University of Michigan

00:31:31.691 --> 00:31:34.177
Dearborn in which we can
create hybrid courses that

00:31:34.177 --> 00:31:36.260
will be offered, and we're
looking for foundations

00:31:36.260 --> 00:31:38.390
to fund those where
some of the courses

00:31:38.390 --> 00:31:40.070
could be held
online in a tablet.

00:31:40.070 --> 00:31:41.980
So they could be
getting academic credit

00:31:41.980 --> 00:31:43.922
doing a course on a
tablet in their cell,

00:31:43.922 --> 00:31:46.130
but also having face-to-face
classes, kind of like we

00:31:46.130 --> 00:31:47.540
have here out on the streets.

00:31:47.540 --> 00:31:49.010
Because there's a lot
of hybrid functionality.

00:31:49.010 --> 00:31:50.990
I don't think we should
have a fully online

00:31:50.990 --> 00:31:53.120
or fully in person, but I
think a blend of the two

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:55.812
integrating technology is great.

00:31:55.812 --> 00:31:56.895
I'm sorry, the other part?

00:31:56.895 --> 00:31:58.030
JACOB SMITH: Challenges.

00:31:58.030 --> 00:32:00.200
AARON KINZEL: Challenges--
getting those tablets

00:32:00.200 --> 00:32:02.300
into the prison system.

00:32:02.300 --> 00:32:05.720
The Department of Corrections
is kind of strange at times.

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:08.600
It's a very strange bird.

00:32:08.600 --> 00:32:11.420
So when they feel that
it is to their advantage,

00:32:11.420 --> 00:32:13.010
they're more open to it.

00:32:13.010 --> 00:32:16.730
And I think what places like
Google and other foundations

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:19.580
that are connected to these
corporate entities can do is

00:32:19.580 --> 00:32:21.624
try to develop relationships
with Department

00:32:21.624 --> 00:32:23.540
of Corrections-- maybe
the Michigan Department

00:32:23.540 --> 00:32:26.840
of Corrections as a start,
other Department of Corrections

00:32:26.840 --> 00:32:28.400
at the federal level state--

00:32:28.400 --> 00:32:31.670
and find ways to
really give them

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:35.000
opportunities to allow
prisoners to have programming

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.895
with these
technological products.

00:32:40.904 --> 00:32:46.340
KARLOS L. HARRIS: So in April,
I did a commencement speech

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:49.310
at Lapeer Correctional
Institution

00:32:49.310 --> 00:32:55.460
for about 53 individuals
who had gained their GED.

00:32:55.460 --> 00:33:00.500
And while there, I was
approached and asked

00:33:00.500 --> 00:33:03.140
if there was a way that we
could actually offer training

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:04.880
at this individual prison.

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:07.130
The prison is the
only one in the state

00:33:07.130 --> 00:33:10.850
that houses youthful offenders.

00:33:10.850 --> 00:33:13.790
And so I actually
proposed to MDOC

00:33:13.790 --> 00:33:17.120
that we would be able to
come in and train them

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:18.510
in digital marketing.

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:19.010
Why?

00:33:19.010 --> 00:33:20.870
Because it saved my life.

00:33:20.870 --> 00:33:21.770
Right?

00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:25.340
And so speaking directly about
the technology, the platform

00:33:25.340 --> 00:33:29.030
that they use is called
Lantern, and it's with JPay.

00:33:29.030 --> 00:33:32.960
The JPay system is the one
that's used statewide in order

00:33:32.960 --> 00:33:34.290
that they would receive--

00:33:34.290 --> 00:33:41.870
whether it be funding, or
media, videos, trainings.

00:33:41.870 --> 00:33:45.200
And the unique thing
about the JPay system

00:33:45.200 --> 00:33:48.320
is that if you are a
educational institution,

00:33:48.320 --> 00:33:51.560
you can set the
platform up at no cost

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:53.610
to the inmates themselves.

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:55.430
And so that's
something that we've

00:33:55.430 --> 00:33:57.200
been working on at the school.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:33:59.150
And I would love to
partner with you guys

00:33:59.150 --> 00:34:01.970
in order to make
that accessible.

00:34:01.970 --> 00:34:06.410
Because one of the
first things that we

00:34:06.410 --> 00:34:08.389
were given the
problem of was, how

00:34:08.389 --> 00:34:11.719
do we get more of the
guys the trainings

00:34:11.719 --> 00:34:13.550
that we have developed?

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.570
And it seemed like the
easiest way was through JPay.

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:19.070
And the wheel doesn't
have to be reinvented.

00:34:19.070 --> 00:34:21.860
It's just a matter of
putting the content together,

00:34:21.860 --> 00:34:23.530
getting it on a system.

00:34:23.530 --> 00:34:25.820
And it's amazing
that I've already

00:34:25.820 --> 00:34:27.920
developed these
relationships that I'm

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:30.120
able to make that happen.

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:33.440
So what are the
unique challenges

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:37.010
that I see as far
as the technology?

00:34:37.010 --> 00:34:39.530
The individuals that
are coming home.

00:34:39.530 --> 00:34:44.150
The ones that I sit and I try
to work with on a daily basis,

00:34:44.150 --> 00:34:48.110
they just have no
idea whatsoever

00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:51.500
of how far this
technology can take them.

00:34:51.500 --> 00:34:53.060
Literally.

00:34:53.060 --> 00:34:55.250
I have guys that
come home and think

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.884
that it's OK to just
post anything on Facebook

00:34:57.884 --> 00:34:59.300
until they go out
to an interview,

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:02.050
and they don't get the job
because of what they posted,

00:35:02.050 --> 00:35:03.560
right?

00:35:03.560 --> 00:35:06.260
I have individuals that
have been returned back

00:35:06.260 --> 00:35:10.280
to prison because of
postings that they made.

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:13.430
So they haven't really
got a fine sense

00:35:13.430 --> 00:35:17.040
of the technology and the
day and age that we live in.

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:19.310
So I think that that's
one of the haphazards

00:35:19.310 --> 00:35:21.770
to the technology piece for
those that are coming on.

00:35:25.847 --> 00:35:27.730
ERIK BURGESS: Piggyback
on what Carlos

00:35:27.730 --> 00:35:31.670
said, Technology is what
I think is going to keep

00:35:31.670 --> 00:35:35.930
most individuals out of prison.

00:35:35.930 --> 00:35:38.230
Fortunately, this is
the way of the world.

00:35:38.230 --> 00:35:41.170
And we must be prepared
and equipped to be

00:35:41.170 --> 00:35:43.470
a part of the world if
we want to be productive.

00:35:43.470 --> 00:35:45.690
Network and technology
got me to this point.

00:35:45.690 --> 00:35:47.342
When I approached Jacob--

00:35:47.342 --> 00:35:48.800
somebody told me
about the podcast.

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:51.270
I was like, how can
I implement this

00:35:51.270 --> 00:35:54.420
in my life to make an impact
all around the world--

00:35:54.420 --> 00:35:56.970
not only just in Wayne
County or Detroit?

00:35:56.970 --> 00:35:58.470
I wanted to make
an impact and share

00:35:58.470 --> 00:36:00.940
my story around the world.

00:36:00.940 --> 00:36:01.930
So I approached Jacob.

00:36:01.930 --> 00:36:03.596
I was like, man, you
heard of a podcast?

00:36:03.596 --> 00:36:06.490
I met Jacob at an
event, just talking.

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:08.115
I'm always talking
and asking question,

00:36:08.115 --> 00:36:09.250
so it didn't make a difference.

00:36:09.250 --> 00:36:10.697
He could have been
four feet tall.

00:36:10.697 --> 00:36:11.863
It didn't make a difference.

00:36:11.863 --> 00:36:12.749
[LAUGHS]

00:36:12.749 --> 00:36:15.040
I was like, Jacob have you
heard of-- introduce myself,

00:36:15.040 --> 00:36:17.720
as everybody did, as such and
such, this amount of time.

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:18.510
He was like, I want
to hear your story.

00:36:18.510 --> 00:36:19.780
I said, have you of
heard of a podcast?

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:20.330
He said, yes.

00:36:20.330 --> 00:36:23.430
So I told him I had an idea,
and we collaborated, and this

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:25.150
is where we are right now.

00:36:25.150 --> 00:36:28.440
And I think the biggest
challenge, the biggest obstacle

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:30.357
for improvement is self.

00:36:30.357 --> 00:36:31.440
That's what it's based on.

00:36:31.440 --> 00:36:32.750
It's based on self.

00:36:32.750 --> 00:36:35.730
So the advancement
is based on yourself

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:36.910
if you want to advance.

00:36:36.910 --> 00:36:39.520
Where your biggest
challenges is is self.

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:41.512
You've got to want to change.

00:36:41.512 --> 00:36:42.720
That's why I want to become--

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:44.010
we've got to want to change.

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:47.590
So self is the biggest
challenge, or self,

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:49.740
is the improvement.

00:36:49.740 --> 00:36:53.040
MICHELLE SMART: I'm going
to have to agree with Eric.

00:36:53.040 --> 00:36:54.210
It is self.

00:36:54.210 --> 00:36:56.790
And I have to be
honest because I'm

00:36:56.790 --> 00:37:00.990
kind of technology challenged
myself in certain areas.

00:37:00.990 --> 00:37:02.370
We have the ladies coming home.

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:04.050
They're getting
these cell phones.

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:06.420
They have no idea
how to use them.

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:10.500
I mean, I pick mine up.

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:13.290
As long as I can say hello
and send a text, I'm good.

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:16.586
Are the apps and all of that
stuff, I don't personally use,

00:37:16.586 --> 00:37:18.210
so we've been trying
to get someone out

00:37:18.210 --> 00:37:21.280
to train the ladies on
using the cell phones.

00:37:21.280 --> 00:37:24.090
I mean, you don't have to speak
with someone with your cell

00:37:24.090 --> 00:37:26.820
phone on speaker,
that type of thing.

00:37:26.820 --> 00:37:28.260
And it's been challenging.

00:37:28.260 --> 00:37:31.110
They have a certain
carrier that they use,

00:37:31.110 --> 00:37:34.050
and just trying to get someone
from that particular carrier

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:37.290
to come out or you know to
help the ladies with that,

00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:41.790
it's been quite difficult.
So I'm kind of guilty myself.

00:37:41.790 --> 00:37:43.870
I don't know a lot
about the technology,

00:37:43.870 --> 00:37:45.600
but I'm learning and
willing to learn.

00:37:47.529 --> 00:37:49.820
JACOB SMITH: But you did
launch an e-commerce business,

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:51.836
which is pretty cool.

00:37:51.836 --> 00:37:53.210
She doesn't know
about technology

00:37:53.210 --> 00:37:55.418
and still launched an
e-commerce business-- testament

00:37:55.418 --> 00:37:56.720
to how far technology's come.

00:37:56.720 --> 00:37:58.880
So now, what we're going
to do is we're actually--

00:37:58.880 --> 00:38:01.380
so as many of the folks tuning
in and the folks in this room

00:38:01.380 --> 00:38:06.200
know, Google is a leader in
the training and education

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:07.200
space around the world.

00:38:07.200 --> 00:38:10.820
I mean, all types of incredible
programs come out of Google.

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:14.450
So I'm going to invite Elyse
Guilfoyle to come rejoin us up

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:16.700
here and tell us a
bit more in detail

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:19.550
about the types of
relevant efforts

00:38:19.550 --> 00:38:20.882
that Google is working on.

00:38:20.882 --> 00:38:22.340
And then, we're
going to kick off--

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:24.800
we took some Q and A
in advance, so we're

00:38:24.800 --> 00:38:27.822
going to kick off the Q and A
and turn it back to the panel.

00:38:27.822 --> 00:38:29.280
ELYSE GUILFOYLE:
Thank you so much.

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:31.010
And thanks everybody
for your perspective

00:38:31.010 --> 00:38:32.218
and sharing your experiences.

00:38:32.218 --> 00:38:35.780
This has been really incredible.

00:38:35.780 --> 00:38:37.340
So some of the
things that Google

00:38:37.340 --> 00:38:39.381
has done I think on a
national level-- and Aaron,

00:38:39.381 --> 00:38:41.630
you mentioned this earlier.

00:38:41.630 --> 00:38:43.640
There's the Ban
the Box initiative.

00:38:43.640 --> 00:38:48.830
And in 2016, Google, along with
a lot of other tech companies,

00:38:48.830 --> 00:38:54.230
pledged to end up having
a box that says, like,

00:38:54.230 --> 00:38:55.940
"have I ever been
convicted of a felony"

00:38:55.940 --> 00:38:59.150
very early on in the process
that removes a lot of people

00:38:59.150 --> 00:39:01.190
from being considered.

00:39:01.190 --> 00:39:04.550
And it doesn't give context
for what they've been through,

00:39:04.550 --> 00:39:07.080
and their experience,
and all of their--

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:09.060
and even qualifications.

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:13.190
So I think our question to
you is, in addition to that--

00:39:13.190 --> 00:39:15.714
and we have a lot of other
smaller local initiatives

00:39:15.714 --> 00:39:18.130
to that are trying to make a
difference for the people who

00:39:18.130 --> 00:39:22.220
have been formerly incarcerated,
but I guess what role do you

00:39:22.220 --> 00:39:26.000
see companies like Google
and other businesses playing

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:29.280
in ex-offenders'
reentry into society

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:30.590
and, especially, the workforce?

00:39:33.092 --> 00:39:34.550
ERIK BURGESS: First
of all, I think

00:39:34.550 --> 00:39:38.150
Google can develop
a platform where

00:39:38.150 --> 00:39:41.570
it can-- a proactive
process, where it can include

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:43.820
diversity and inclusion.

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:47.510
Myself, I'm working on a
social entrepreneur business

00:39:47.510 --> 00:39:48.470
as far as--

00:39:48.470 --> 00:39:50.320
it's called Digit 650.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:51.860
And the reason I
call Digit 650 is

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:55.610
because the way we communicate
in the world is digital.

00:39:55.610 --> 00:39:57.600
And 650, I was convicted.

00:39:57.600 --> 00:39:58.250
That's my past.

00:39:58.250 --> 00:40:01.430
I was convicted under
the 650 drug-lifer law.

00:40:01.430 --> 00:40:03.640
So that's why I
call it Digit 650,

00:40:03.640 --> 00:40:06.700
where I can make my past
make an imprint on the future

00:40:06.700 --> 00:40:12.330
and where my goal is to go
into the juvenile court system

00:40:12.330 --> 00:40:14.760
and try to eliminate
FTAs, which FTAs stand

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:17.960
for "failure to appear"
due to the lack of probably

00:40:17.960 --> 00:40:21.650
transportation or any
external or internal factors

00:40:21.650 --> 00:40:22.580
the parents may have.

00:40:22.580 --> 00:40:30.750
75% of Wayne County families
have smartphones, and 60% or so

00:40:30.750 --> 00:40:32.930
of families do not
have transportation.

00:40:32.930 --> 00:40:37.400
So any low-income defendants
who may have trouble or somehow

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:39.590
impeding transportation
or any other inconvenience

00:40:39.590 --> 00:40:46.560
to get to court, my goal is to
have a virtual hearing court

00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:50.270
session for nonviolent offenders
or whatever through mobile.

00:40:50.270 --> 00:40:52.370
It can be mobile,
iPad, or computer.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:40:57.960
Google shouldn't have to put
any money into this system.

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:00.530
If they just have the
willingness to be involved--

00:41:00.530 --> 00:41:02.990
companies like that, just the
willingness to be involved.

00:41:02.990 --> 00:41:04.882
It's not all about
financial gain.

00:41:04.882 --> 00:41:06.590
So it's about willingness
to be involved,

00:41:06.590 --> 00:41:10.280
having compassion,
and having a purpose.

00:41:10.280 --> 00:41:13.820
So that's why I feel Google
and any other organization that

00:41:13.820 --> 00:41:18.440
can help be proactive-- and I'm
looking for reactionary aspect.

00:41:18.440 --> 00:41:20.390
Because we have a
lot of reactionary

00:41:20.390 --> 00:41:21.870
organizations out here.

00:41:21.870 --> 00:41:23.420
But like I say,
my goal is really

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:26.750
to change this title of "The
Returning Citizen Podcast"

00:41:26.750 --> 00:41:33.670
and change it to "Not to Become
a Returning Citizen" soon.

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:36.750
KARLOS L. HARRIS: So
if I had a wish list--

00:41:36.750 --> 00:41:38.520
I have this thing
where I say we have

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:39.990
to hold their feet to the fire.

00:41:42.770 --> 00:41:45.120
Although there's a
lot of propaganda

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:47.250
about returning
citizens and having

00:41:47.250 --> 00:41:50.970
second chances, in truth,
that's all that it is at times

00:41:50.970 --> 00:41:52.920
is propaganda.

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:56.310
Last year, we graduated
about 185 individuals

00:41:56.310 --> 00:41:58.080
through our programs.

00:41:58.080 --> 00:42:00.720
And a huge portion of them
were returning citizens.

00:42:00.720 --> 00:42:02.970
And at the end of the day,
it's still difficult for us

00:42:02.970 --> 00:42:05.520
to find employment
opportunities for them.

00:42:05.520 --> 00:42:08.354
I don't care if the Ban the
Box initiative doesn't pass.

00:42:08.354 --> 00:42:10.020
Whatever the situation
is, it's the fact

00:42:10.020 --> 00:42:12.030
that their background
still follow them.

00:42:12.030 --> 00:42:14.070
So if companies like
Google, who have

00:42:14.070 --> 00:42:18.510
come into perhaps
one of the cities

00:42:18.510 --> 00:42:21.540
within the state where the most
returning citizens are coming

00:42:21.540 --> 00:42:24.270
back to, would actually
take up the initiative

00:42:24.270 --> 00:42:26.880
to offer some sort
of -level positions

00:42:26.880 --> 00:42:28.470
to some of these
offenders, that would

00:42:28.470 --> 00:42:32.340
be huge within our community.

00:42:32.340 --> 00:42:34.260
As well as if
there was some sort

00:42:34.260 --> 00:42:38.700
of incentives behind your
entrepreneur endeavors.

00:42:38.700 --> 00:42:41.180
A lot of us are
entrepreneurial-minded.

00:42:41.180 --> 00:42:43.890
And if we had an
opportunity to actually find

00:42:43.890 --> 00:42:47.430
some sort of funding for
the ideas that we had,

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:49.630
that would be huge
for us as well.

00:42:49.630 --> 00:42:55.080
So I think that those pairings
would offer a great opportunity

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:58.980
for those within the community
to accelerate their return

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:02.114
and be more successful.

00:43:02.114 --> 00:43:04.550
AARON KINZEL: So I take
it even to a higher level.

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:07.040
I mean, there's a lot of
formerly incarcerated people

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:09.830
that could go well beyond
entry-level position.

00:43:09.830 --> 00:43:11.360
So I really
encourage you to look

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:15.830
at people who could be at
the administrative level,

00:43:15.830 --> 00:43:18.664
perhaps on a foundation
board, or maybe even create

00:43:18.664 --> 00:43:20.330
a panel of formerly
incarcerated people.

00:43:20.330 --> 00:43:23.330
If you want to work on
reforming the system

00:43:23.330 --> 00:43:26.180
and give back through
corporate donations,

00:43:26.180 --> 00:43:28.640
you need a panel of people
that have been justice-involved

00:43:28.640 --> 00:43:30.560
and also survivors of crime.

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:32.490
People always leave them
out of the equation.

00:43:32.490 --> 00:43:35.660
You need survivors of crime who
are people on the streets that

00:43:35.660 --> 00:43:38.360
have been subjected to criminal
activity and also people

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:40.070
that have been in
the carceral state,

00:43:40.070 --> 00:43:42.320
and then mix it up with
random other community members

00:43:42.320 --> 00:43:44.346
to kind of really find a way--

00:43:44.346 --> 00:43:46.220
what are the programs
that are worth funding?

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:48.320
What do you want to
throw your dollars at?

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:50.600
And find some really
bright individuals

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:53.180
who have gained
academic credentials,

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:56.960
professional credentials,
technological credentials that

00:43:56.960 --> 00:44:00.480
can really help expand Google
in completely different ways.

00:44:00.480 --> 00:44:02.540
And I really challenge Google.

00:44:02.540 --> 00:44:05.750
Think about ways how you
can really invest technology

00:44:05.750 --> 00:44:07.455
into prisons and jails.

00:44:07.455 --> 00:44:09.830
And also, youth facility--
that's another thing we rarely

00:44:09.830 --> 00:44:10.670
talk about--

00:44:10.670 --> 00:44:13.020
these juvenile detention
facilities nationwide,

00:44:13.020 --> 00:44:14.570
where youth are often forgotten.

00:44:14.570 --> 00:44:16.550
If anybody deserves
a second chance,

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:19.070
it's someone under the age 18.

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:21.980
Kids should definitely never be
just the snapshot of one thing

00:44:21.980 --> 00:44:25.170
that they've done in their life.

