00:50:45.530 --> 00:50:47.785
So all you have to do is ask.

00:50:47.785 --> 00:50:49.450
Our family and friends--

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:51.120
a huge organization.

00:50:51.120 --> 00:50:54.086
So that's where it starts.

00:50:54.086 --> 00:50:55.460
ELYSE GUILFOYLE: Thank you.

00:50:55.460 --> 00:50:57.690
Our last question is
a little off topic,

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:01.517
but it's very timely as we
approach the midterm elections.

00:51:01.517 --> 00:51:04.100
The question is, what are your
thoughts on states like Florida

00:51:04.100 --> 00:51:06.800
putting the removal of
felony disenfranchisement

00:51:06.800 --> 00:51:09.380
on the ballot, and how can we
support initiatives like this

00:51:09.380 --> 00:51:12.230
to enable ex-felons beyond
education, even if we

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:14.400
don't live in those states?

00:51:14.400 --> 00:51:16.790
KARLOS L. HARRIS: Please
let me tackle this one.

00:51:16.790 --> 00:51:18.290
Please.

00:51:18.290 --> 00:51:23.240
All right, so we're part
of a accreditation process

00:51:23.240 --> 00:51:28.130
organization called Council
on Occupational Education.

00:51:28.130 --> 00:51:33.620
And so we are slated to
be in Florida the 5th

00:51:33.620 --> 00:51:36.500
through the 9th of November.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:40.760
And I am watching this
election so heavily right now.

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:42.950
Because I'm really
at odds with going

00:51:42.950 --> 00:51:45.950
to a state where my
community doesn't even

00:51:45.950 --> 00:51:48.120
have the right to vote.

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:54.910
So for me, my trip is
literally in the hangar,

00:51:54.910 --> 00:52:00.910
as it's decided whether or not
the right to vote by ex-felons

00:52:00.910 --> 00:52:03.160
will be granted once again.

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:06.340
I think that the process that
they've been implementing

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:09.910
over the years is archaic.

00:52:09.910 --> 00:52:12.870
I cherish my right to vote.

00:52:12.870 --> 00:52:14.390
Now think about this.

00:52:14.390 --> 00:52:16.790
I'm the guy whose
driver's license

00:52:16.790 --> 00:52:19.940
was suspended for 18 years.

00:52:19.940 --> 00:52:22.640
And I had more suspended
license tickets,

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:24.740
and I've been in
jails and prisons,

00:52:24.740 --> 00:52:30.490
but yet, at every opportunity
I had to vote, I was there.

00:52:30.490 --> 00:52:33.790
And my children,
they're 18 and 20 now.

00:52:33.790 --> 00:52:38.020
They vote because their
father was there taking them.

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:42.400
So I don't take lightly the fact
of people being disenfranchised

00:52:42.400 --> 00:52:44.680
within my community
because they're not

00:52:44.680 --> 00:52:46.130
afforded the right to vote.

00:52:46.130 --> 00:52:48.640
I think that it's a right
that we're all entitled to,

00:52:48.640 --> 00:52:50.800
regardless of our backgrounds.

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:55.620
And we should be afforded the
opportunity to exercise it.

00:52:55.620 --> 00:52:57.620
JACOB SMITH: Anyone else
want to weigh in there?

00:52:57.620 --> 00:53:02.384
And I just want to point
out-- so in Michigan, formerly

00:53:02.384 --> 00:53:03.800
incarcerated
individuals can vote.

00:53:03.800 --> 00:53:06.830
Can you vote while
you're in prison?

00:53:06.830 --> 00:53:09.260
Will you explain the climate
in Michigan currently?

00:53:09.260 --> 00:53:14.180
AARON KINZEL: So as a pretrial
detainee in a county jail,

00:53:14.180 --> 00:53:16.880
you're allowed to vote
if you're not convicted.

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:19.590
Once you are sentenced in
the county jail or you go off

00:53:19.590 --> 00:53:21.650
to prison, you cannot
vote in Michigan.

00:53:21.650 --> 00:53:24.380
There are two states--

00:53:24.380 --> 00:53:25.985
one was Maine, and
I believe the other

00:53:25.985 --> 00:53:29.420
is Vermont where you can
actually vote absentee ballot

00:53:29.420 --> 00:53:30.590
in a prison setting.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:36.410
So we've got a 2.3 million
people inside right now.

00:53:36.410 --> 00:53:38.000
That's a huge voting block.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.740
And now if you take that
and you look at nationally--

00:53:41.740 --> 00:53:43.610
there's different
stats that say this--

00:53:43.610 --> 00:53:46.250
but roughly 70 million
Americans have some type

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:48.740
of criminal justice history--
whether that's an arrest,

00:53:48.740 --> 00:53:51.050
a conviction, a
juvie bit, whatever.

00:53:51.050 --> 00:53:51.990
They have something.

00:53:51.990 --> 00:53:53.780
So think about that
as a voting block.

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:56.240
So to piggyback off
what Carlos said,

00:53:56.240 --> 00:53:58.100
I'm actually
working on something

00:53:58.100 --> 00:54:01.220
with the Soros Justice
Fellowship Project,

00:54:01.220 --> 00:54:04.370
where I'm trying to create this
carceral state public policy

00:54:04.370 --> 00:54:06.710
training academy which
would empower formerly

00:54:06.710 --> 00:54:09.200
incarcerated people,
survivors of crime,

00:54:09.200 --> 00:54:13.340
not only to register to vote
and vote, but to educate them.

00:54:13.340 --> 00:54:15.590
Because a lot of people
who go out and vote

00:54:15.590 --> 00:54:17.480
are uneducated
voters, unfortunately.

00:54:17.480 --> 00:54:18.990
That's just the reality.

00:54:18.990 --> 00:54:23.210
So create a platform that
is criminal justice minded.

00:54:23.210 --> 00:54:24.470
What are the important issues?

00:54:24.470 --> 00:54:26.810
Like, for instance,
mandatory minimum,

00:54:26.810 --> 00:54:29.390
solitary confinement,
abolishing the death penalty,

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:31.280
et cetera, et cetera.

00:54:31.280 --> 00:54:34.160
Create a voting block that
is focused on these issues.

00:54:34.160 --> 00:54:36.080
Secondary to that,
we need to have

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:38.000
people mobilize in
their communities

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:40.790
and have formerly incarcerated
people and survivors of crime

00:54:40.790 --> 00:54:42.740
run for elected offices.

00:54:42.740 --> 00:54:45.440
It seems real simple, but a lot
of people are scared to do it.

00:54:45.440 --> 00:54:47.420
Local, state, and
federal level, if you

00:54:47.420 --> 00:54:50.840
add those 70 million people in
this country, and their family,

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:52.749
and friends, that's half
of this country now.

00:54:52.749 --> 00:54:54.290
Think about the
changes that we could

00:54:54.290 --> 00:54:57.800
have if we got all those people,
or even just 10% or 20% of them

00:54:57.800 --> 00:55:00.590
that could really dramatically
change not just this midterm

00:55:00.590 --> 00:55:03.590
election, but come 2020,
I know a certain person

00:55:03.590 --> 00:55:07.615
I want to vote the hell out
of office very, very much.

00:55:07.615 --> 00:55:09.740
And there's a lot of other
congressional reps, too,

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:11.492
and state level,
and local level.

00:55:11.492 --> 00:55:12.950
Because they are
not representative

00:55:12.950 --> 00:55:14.390
of a lot of our interests.

00:55:14.390 --> 00:55:16.610
I find that, now, we
have corporate policy.

00:55:16.610 --> 00:55:18.110
And no offense to
Google right here,

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:21.890
but I feel that we need
to find more ways that

00:55:21.890 --> 00:55:25.850
are more beneficial to citizens
as opposed to corporations,

00:55:25.850 --> 00:55:27.330
so that's my platform on that.

00:55:30.550 --> 00:55:33.630
JACOB SMITH: And just to clarify
for anyone who is formerly

00:55:33.630 --> 00:55:35.940
incarcerated or the families
of folks that are formerly

00:55:35.940 --> 00:55:38.710
incarcerated, you
can vote in Michigan

00:55:38.710 --> 00:55:40.680
if you're formerly
incarcerated-- so just to be

00:55:40.680 --> 00:55:42.670
super clear on that topic.

00:55:42.670 --> 00:55:45.420
I think a lot of folks are
intimidated, or confused,

00:55:45.420 --> 00:55:47.510
and don't realize that
they are able to vote.

00:55:47.510 --> 00:55:49.290
AARON KINZEL: They think
it doesn't matter as well.

00:55:49.290 --> 00:55:50.690
They think they're
vote doesn't matter.

00:55:50.690 --> 00:55:52.773
JACOB SMITH: They think
their vote doesn't matter.

00:55:52.773 --> 00:55:54.962
So, yeah, please,
everybody vote.

00:55:54.962 --> 00:55:55.920
ELYSE GUILFOYLE: Great.

00:55:55.920 --> 00:55:58.270
Thank you everybody so
